      <div xml:id="NA221-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu viṉaimuṟṟi maṟuttarāniṉṟa talaimakaṉ (EV: mīḷkiṉṟa talaivaṉ) pākaṟkuc colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what HE said, who was bringing back [his] wealth after having accomplished [it], to the charioteer.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA221">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            maṇikaṇ ṭaṉṉa māniṟak karuviḷai</l>
<l>            yoṇpūn tōṉṟiyoṭu taṇputa laṇiyap</l>
<l>            poṉṟoṭarn taṉṉa takaiya naṉmalark</l>
<l>            koṉṟai yoḷḷiṇar kōṭutoṟun tūṅka</l>
<l>            vampuvirit taṉṉa cempulap puṟavi </l>
<l>            ṉīraṇi peruvaḻi nīḷiṭaip pōḻac</l>
<l>            celka pākaniṉ ceyviṉai neṭuntēr</l>
<l>            viruntu viruppuṟūum peruntōṭ kuṟumakaṇ</l>
<l>            miṉṉoḷi raviriḻai naṉṉakar viḷaṅka</l>
<l>            naṭaināṭ ceyta navilāc cīṟaṭip </l>
<l>            pūṅkaṭ putalvaṉ ṟūṅkuvayi ṉolki</l>
<l>            vantī kentai yeṉṉu</l>
<l>            mantīṅ kiḷavi kēṭka nāmē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent2">While mussel-shell creepers of dark colour looking like sapphires</l>
<l rend="indent2">adorn together with bright-flowered Malabar lilies the cool bushes,</l>
<l rend="indent2">while good flowers wound as linked gold</l>
<l rend="indent2">are hanging in every bright-clustered branch of the Laburnum trees,</l>
<l rend="indent3">as if news had spread(?),<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vampu virittu aṉṉa</term>: T.V.G. explains <term xml:lang="ta">vampu</term> here to mean "blanket" (without parallels, unsupported by the dictionaries) and takes it as a simile for the red soil. If we take it in the sense of "novelty", it might be an image of the plants* reaction to the onset of the rains: they all "know" it already and have flowered.</note> in the red-soiled woodland,</l>
<l>– to cross the long way, the great route adorned with water</l>
<l>may your long chariot for the work that is done(?)<note place="foot">Does <term xml:lang="ta">cey viṉai</term> refer back to the past function of the chariot, namely the vehicle they used on their quest? Or is it actually supposed to be an attribute of the chariot: a chariot doing its work?</note> go, charioteer.</l>
<l>Let us hear the pretty sweet words</l>
<l rend="indent3">*let my father come!* that are said,<note place="foot">T.V.G. interprets the syntax of these lines completely differently, namely to the effect that these are the words said by the mother when awakening the child in the morning. But, apart from the clause syntax of lines 10-12 (which is as sparse and ambiguous as ever), would a mother really address her child as <term xml:lang="ta">entai</term></note></l>
<l rend="indent2">bending over to one side(?), by [my] flower-eyed son</l>
<l rend="indent2">with [his] unpractised small feet that have done walking in the morning(?),</l>
<l rend="indent">as the good mansion shines with shining jewels, resplendent with flashes,</l>
<l>of the broad-shouldered little woman who has longing for a feast.<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">viruntu viṟuppu uṟūum</term>: I see here a reference to the imminent feast celebrated on HIS arrival. T.V.G. however takes it as HER inherent desire to entertain guests.</note></l>
        </lg>
      </div>
